post_cb({"19364690": {"ParentId": "19364635", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>A <code>break</code> statement ends only the <code>do</code>, <code>for</code>, <code>switch</code>, or <code>while</code> statement that immediately encloses it.  It doesn't break out of an if statement, so your code is breaking out of the loop.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "1288", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "19364690", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2013-10-14T16:22:00.497", "LastActivityDate": "2013-10-14T16:22:00.497"}, "19364635": {"CommentCount": "5", "ViewCount": "98", "CreationDate": "2013-10-14T16:18:10.830", "LastActivityDate": "2013-10-15T01:55:29.510", "Title": "Is it break my for loop in c++?", "AcceptedAnswerId": "19364732", "PostTypeId": "1", "Id": "19364635", "Score": "1", "Body": "<pre><code>for(size_t i=0;i&lt;vec.size();i++){\n    if(n&gt;vec[i]){\n        a=i;\n        break;\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>in this example, am I breaking the if statement or the for loop?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><for-loop><break>", "OwnerUserId": "2879588", "AnswerCount": "3"}, "19364673": {"ParentId": "19364635", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>It will break from the <strong>for</strong> loop.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_19364635_19364673_0\">In loops, the break statement ends execution of the nearest enclosing\n  <strong>do</strong>, <strong>for</strong>, or <strong>while</strong> statement.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><strong>Source:</strong> <a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/37zc9d2w.aspx\" rel=\"nofollow\">Microsoft docs</a></p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "1503646", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "19364673", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2013-10-14T16:21:00.283", "LastActivityDate": "2013-10-14T16:21:00.283"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_19364635_19364732_0": {"section_id": 3910, "quality": 0.95, "length": 19}}, "n3337": {"so_19364635_19364732_0": {"section_id": 3770, "quality": 0.95, "length": 19}}, "n4659": {"so_19364635_19364732_0": {"section_id": 4796, "quality": 0.95, "length": 19}}}, "19364732": {"ParentId": "19364635", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "0", "Body": "<p>The <em>break</em> statement is used to break out of a <em>switch</em> or <em>iteration statement</em> i.e. a while, do or for loop. The <a href=\"http://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/docs/papers/2012/n3485.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">C++ draft standard </a>section <code>6.6.1</code> <em>The break statement</em> says:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_19364635_19364732_0\">The break statement shall occur only in an iteration-statement or a switch statement and causes termination of the smallest enclosing iteration-statement or switch statement; control passes to the statement following the terminated statement, if any.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Since the <em>if</em> is not an <em>iteration statement</em> or a <em>switch</em> then the <em>break</em> will leave the <em>for</em> loop.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "1708801", "LastEditorUserId": "1708801", "LastEditDate": "2013-10-15T01:55:29.510", "Id": "19364732", "Score": "4", "CreationDate": "2013-10-14T16:24:13.627", "LastActivityDate": "2013-10-15T01:55:29.510"}});